  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Developing Strategies for Change for Women Workers in African Horticulture</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">In the textile factories of Madagascar and Lesotho between 80-99% of workers are women, yet they have not generally been able to take full leadership roles or have their specific needs for maternity leave and reproductive health addressed. Women Working Worldwide supports 10,000 women garment workers in Madagascar and Lesotho through training to understand their rights and strengthen their negotiating power with factory owners and managers. The aim is to improve basic rates of pay and conditions through collective bargaining. Women leaders are able to link up with other garment worker unions in Bangladesh and India, and to undertake advocacy with international retailers to convince managers and owners to improve conditions and open up new opportunities for purchases from their factories.</narrative>
  </description>
